<Layout title="How to Read a Wine Label" description="Decode wine labels like a pro — everything you need to know about what's on the bottle and what it means.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Learn</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">How to Read a Wine Label</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 9 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">A wine label is a compressed data sheet — producer, origin, grape, vintage, quality level, and regulatory compliance, all packed into a few square inches. Once you learn to read it, every bottle tells you something useful before you even pull the cork.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">New World vs. Old World Labels</h2>
      <p>The biggest difference in wine labeling is philosophical. <strong>New World</strong> producers (US, Australia, Chile, Argentina, New Zealand, South Africa) typically label by <em>grape variety</em> — you'll see "Cabernet Sauvignon" or "Chardonnay" prominently displayed. <strong>Old World</strong> producers (France, Italy, Spain, Germany) traditionally label by <em>region</em> — so you need to know that "Chablis" means Chardonnay, "Barolo" means Nebbiolo, and "Sancerre" means Sauvignon Blanc.</p>
      <p>This is why Old World labels can feel more intimidating — they assume you already know the local grape-to-region mapping. But this system also encodes much more information: a regional label tells you not just the grape, but the climate, soil type, winemaking traditions, and quality standards that shaped the wine.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Key Label Elements</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Producer / Estate Name</h3>
      <p>Usually the most prominent text. In Burgundy, the producer matters more than almost anything else — the same vineyard farmed by different winemakers can yield radically different wines. In Bordeaux, the château name <em>is</em> the brand. In Napa, the winery name is front and center.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Appellation / Region</h3>
      <p>Where the grapes were grown. Appellations range from broad (e.g., "Bourgogne" = all of Burgundy) to hyper-specific (e.g., "Chambertin Grand Cru" = a single 32-acre vineyard). Generally, the more specific the appellation, the higher the expected quality — and price.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Vintage</h3>
      <p>The year the grapes were harvested. This matters because growing conditions vary year to year, especially in marginal climates. A 2015 Barolo and a 2014 Barolo can be dramatically different wines. Non-vintage (NV) wines — common in Champagne — blend multiple years for consistency.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Grape Variety</h3>
      <p>Listed on most New World labels. In the US, a wine labeled "Cabernet Sauvignon" must contain at least 75% of that variety. In the EU, it's typically 85%. If no grape is listed, the appellation name implies the variety (or blend).</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Alcohol by Volume (ABV)</h3>
      <p>Listed as a percentage. This tells you about the wine's body and style. Under 12% = light-bodied (Moscato, German Riesling). 12.5–13.5% = medium-bodied (Pinot Noir, Chablis). 14–15%+ = full-bodied (Napa Cabernet, Barossa Shiraz, Amarone).</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Quality Classification</h3>
      <p>Many countries have official quality hierarchies. Key ones to know:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>France:</strong> AOC/AOP (highest, regulated origin) → IGP (regional, more flexible) → Vin de France (basic)</li>
        <li><strong>Italy:</strong> DOCG (highest, guaranteed origin) → DOC (controlled origin) → IGT (regional) → Vino da Tavola</li>
        <li><strong>Spain:</strong> DOCa/DOQ (highest) → DO → Vino de la Tierra → Vino de Mesa</li>
        <li><strong>Germany:</strong> Prädikatswein (classified by ripeness level: Kabinett → Spätlese → Auslese → Beerenauslese → Trockenbeerenauslese)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Terms You'll See</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Réserve / Riserva / Reserva:</strong> In Italy and Spain, this has legal meaning — the wine was aged for a minimum period before release. In France and the US, it's essentially meaningless marketing.</li>
        <li><strong>Estate Bottled / Mis en bouteille au château:</strong> The producer grew, vinified, and bottled the wine on their property. Generally a sign of quality control.</li>
        <li><strong>Old Vines / Vieilles Vignes:</strong> Grapes from older vines (no legal definition of "old," but typically 40+ years). Older vines produce less fruit but often more concentrated, complex wine.</li>
        <li><strong>Unfiltered / Non-filtré:</strong> The wine wasn't filtered before bottling, which can preserve more flavor but may result in harmless sediment.</li>
        <li><strong>Contains Sulfites:</strong> Required on US labels. Nearly all wines contain sulfites (a natural byproduct of fermentation). This is not a meaningful quality indicator.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Back Label</h2>
      <p>Often more useful than the front. Back labels may include tasting notes, food pairing suggestions, vineyard details, aging information (e.g., "18 months in French oak"), and import/distribution information. Read it — especially if the front label is in a language you don't speak.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Practice Exercise</h2>
      <p>Next time you buy a bottle, spend 60 seconds with the label before opening it. Identify: producer, region, grape (stated or implied), vintage, ABV, and quality classification. Then taste the wine and see if the label's clues match what's in the glass. A 14.5% ABV Barolo Riserva should taste very different from a 12% ABV Bourgogne Rouge — and now you'll know why before you even pour.</p>
